The shrine, originally called Torino Shrine, is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where the "Torino Shrine of Chikuzen Province" is recorded as receiving a Rank promotion in {{ill|873|ja|貞観15th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. During the medieval period, the shrine was revered by the {{ill|Aso clan|ja|麻生氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and in the early modern period, it became a tutelary shrine for Kurosaki and Fujita under the patronage of the {{ill|Kuroda clan|ja|黒田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. 

Later, it came to honor Kuroda Yoshitaka, his son Kuroda Nagamasa, and 24 loyal warriors of the Kuroda family. Throughout the Edo period, it was referred to as "Kuroda Daimyōjin" or "Black Warrior Daimyōjin." In the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the shrine was renamed Kasuga-no-miya. It was designated a {{ill|Murasha|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|1872|ja|明治5th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and promoted to a {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|県社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|1937|ja|昭和12nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

