Later, it came to honor Kuroda Yoshitaka, his son Kuroda Nagamasa, and 24 loyal warriors of the Kuroda family. Throughout the Edo period, it was referred to as "Kuroda Daimyōjin" or "Black Warrior Daimyōjin." In the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji period|qq=}}, the shrine was renamed Kasuga-no-miya. It was designated a {{ill|Murasha|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murasha|qq=}} in {{ill|1872|ja|明治5th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1872|qq=}} and promoted to a {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|県社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ken-sha|qq=}} in {{ill|1937|ja|昭和12nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1937|qq=}}.

== Festivals ==
* '''Kurosaki Gion Yamakasa''': July 21–23. A famous summer festival where portable shrines (yamakasa) are paraded.
* '''Autumn Grand Festival''': October 15. The shrine’s annual major festival.

== Access ==
* '''By Train''': 10 minutes on foot from {{ill|Kurosaki Station|ja|黒崎駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurosaki Station|qq=}} (JR Kyushu).
* '''By Car''': Accessible via nearby roads and parking facilities.

