'''Kasuga Shrine''' (春日神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in the {{ill|Kurosaki, Kitakyushu|ja|黒崎|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurosaki, Kitakyushu|qq=}} area of {{ill|Yahatanishi-ku|ja|八幡西区|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yahatanishi-ku|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. The shrine is also referred to as Kasuga-no-miya, Torino Shrine, or Kuroda Shrine. It is associated with the {{ill|Kokushi-genzai-sha|ja|国史見在社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi-genzai-sha|qq=}} mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}}, but this attribution is debated.<ref>The "Torino Shrine of Chikuzen Province" is more commonly associated with {{ill|Torino Shrine (Nōgata)|ja|鳥野神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Torino Shrine (Nōgata)|qq=}} in {{ill|Nōgata|ja|直方市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nōgata|qq=}}. See: ''Shinto Taijiten'', Heibonsha, 1939.</ref> The shrine is renowned for the {{ill|Kurosaki Gion Yamakasa|ja|黒崎祇園山笠|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurosaki Gion Yamakasa|qq=}}, a celebrated summer festival.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines the {{ill|Kasuga-no-Kami|ja|春日四神|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kasuga-no-Kami|qq=}}:
* {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}}
* {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futsunushi|qq=}}
* [[Ame-no-Koyane]]
* {{ill|Himegami|ja|比売神|lt=Hime no Kami|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Himegami|qq=}}

Additionally, it honors the founding lord of {{ill|Fukuoka Domain|ja|福岡藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Domain|qq=}}, {{ill|Kuroda Yoshitaka|ja|黒田孝高|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda Yoshitaka|qq=}} (Kuroda Kanbei), the first feudal lord {{ill|Kuroda Nagamasa|ja|黒田長政|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda Nagamasa|qq=}} (Black Warrior Daimyōjin), and the {{ill|Kuroda 24 Generals|ja|黒田二十四騎|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda 24 Generals|qq=}}, a group of notable warriors who served the Kuroda family.

== History ==
The shrine, originally called Torino Shrine, is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}}, where the "Torino Shrine of Chikuzen Province" is recorded as receiving a Rank promotion in {{ill|873|ja|貞観15th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/873|qq=}}. During the medieval period, the shrine was revered by the {{ill|Aso clan|ja|麻生氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso clan|qq=}}, and in the early modern period, it became a tutelary shrine for Kurosaki and Fujita under the patronage of the {{ill|Kuroda clan|ja|黒田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda clan|qq=}}. 

Later, it came to honor Kuroda Yoshitaka, his son Kuroda Nagamasa, and 24 loyal warriors of the Kuroda family. Throughout the Edo period, it was referred to as "Kuroda Daimyōjin" or "Black Warrior Daimyōjin." In the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|2=ja|3=明治|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji period|qq=}}, the shrine was renamed Kasuga-no-miya. It was designated a {{ill|Murasha|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murasha|qq=}} in {{ill|1872|ja|明治5th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1872|qq=}} and promoted to a {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|県社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ken-sha|qq=}} in {{ill|1937|ja|昭和12nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1937|qq=}}.

== Festivals ==
* '''Kurosaki Gion Yamakasa''': July 21–23. A famous summer festival where portable shrines (yamakasa) are paraded.
* '''Autumn Grand Festival''': October 15. The shrine’s annual major festival.

== Access ==
* '''By Train''': 10 minutes on foot from {{ill|Kurosaki Station|ja|黒崎駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurosaki Station|qq=}} (JR Kyushu).
* '''By Car''': Accessible via nearby roads and parking facilities.

