Additionally, it honors the founding lord of [[:en:Fukuoka Domain|Fukuoka Domain]], [[:en:Kuroda Yoshitaka|Kuroda Yoshitaka]] (Kuroda Kanbei), the first feudal lord [[:en:Kuroda Nagamasa|Kuroda Nagamasa]] (Black Warrior Daimyōjin), and the {{ill|Kuroda 24 Generals|ja|黒田二十四騎|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda 24 Generals|qq=|1=Kuroda Nijūyonki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q2027225}}, a group of notable warriors who served the Kuroda family.

== History ==
The shrine, originally called Torino Shrine, is mentioned in the [[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]], where the "Torino Shrine of Chikuzen Province" is recorded as receiving a Rank promotion in {{ill|873|ja|貞観15年|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/873|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135579686}}. During the medieval period, the shrine was revered by the {{ill|Aso clan|ja|麻生氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso clan|qq=}}, and in the early modern period, it became a tutelary shrine for Kurosaki and Fujita under the patronage of the [[:en:Kuroda clan|Kuroda clan]]. 

Later, it came to honor Kuroda Yoshitaka, his son Kuroda Nagamasa, and 24 loyal warriors of the Kuroda family. Throughout the Edo period, it was referred to as "Kuroda Daimyōjin" or "Black Warrior Daimyōjin." In the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]], the shrine was renamed Kasuga-no-miya. It was designated a {{ill|Murasha|ja|村社|1=Son-sha|qid=Q134917284}}{{efn|Former shrine rank|lt=Son-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Murasha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki s to 近代社格制度|ja_comment=jawiki s to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} in [[:en:1872|Meiji 5]] replacements]] and promoted to a {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|県社|1=Prefectural Shrine|qid=Q90139226}}{{efn|Ken-sha|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ken-sha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki s to 近代社格制度|ja_comment=jawiki s to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} in [[:en:1937|Showa 12]] replacements]].

== Festivals ==
* '''Kurosaki Gion Yamakasa''': July 21–23. A famous summer festival where portable shrines (yamakasa) are paraded.
* '''Autumn Grand Festival''': October 15. The shrine’s annual major festival.

== Access ==
* '''By Train''': 10 minutes on foot from [[:en:Kurosaki Station|Kurosaki Station]] (JR Kyushu).
* '''By Car''': Accessible via nearby roads and parking facilities.

